T1  - A Comparison of Moral Reasoning of Groups and Individuals on the “Defining Issues Test”
AU  - Nichols, Mary Lippitt
AU  - Day, Victoria E.
Y1  - 1982/03/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256035
DO  - 10.5465/256035
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 201
EP  - 208
VL  - 25
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents a study which compared the moral reasoning of interacting groups and the reasoning of individual members of the group using the defining issues test (DIT) of moral judgement development. The results showed that interacting groups reason at a significantly higher level, as measured by the DIT, than the average of the members of the groups. Although the results are interesting and perhaps promising, at this stage they are subject to limitations. Thus, additional research on the issue seems justified.
AB  - The article presents a study which compared the moral reasoning of interacting groups and the reasoning of individual members of the group using the defining issues test (DIT) of moral judgement development. The results showed that interacting groups reason at a significantly higher level, as measured by the DIT, than the average of the members of the groups. Although the results are interesting and perhaps promising, at this stage they are subject to limitations. Thus, additional research on the issue seems justified.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256035
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256035
Y2  - 2026/04/24
